Long QT syndrome (LQTS) is a disorder of the heart in which there is a prolongation of the QT interval on electrocardiogram (ECG).  The prolongation of the QT interval is due to an abnormally long delay between electrical excitation (or depolarization) and relaxation (or repolarization) of the ventricles of the heart.  This condition is associated with exercise or startle related syncope (loss of consciousness), sudden death (due to ventricular arrhythmias) and unexplained drowning.